      "\n- \n  - Five energy levels are drawn, labeled $n = 1$ to $n = 5$ with the higher energy levels converging as the energy level increases. $\\checkmark$\n    The transition arrow is drawn in an upward direction from $n = 2$ to $n = 5$. $\\checkmark$\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/a6193c6a-debf-439d-8c72-9e31753671f2/images/762a2896-5d31-4ed2-bd34-68a4302304b2/CH0785.png)\n\n\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    The lines representing the energy levels must converge at higher levels because the energy levels within the atom converge away from the nucleus. The arrow must begin at $n = 2$ and point to $n = 5$ to indicate the direction of the transition.\n  - Energy must be absorbed for the electron to move away from a position closer to the nucleus ($n = 2$) to a position further from the nucleus ($n = 5$). Therefore, the absorption spectrum would show the wavelength of light energy absorbed to cause this transition. $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    Although the electron has more kinetic energy closer to the nucleus, the electron has more potential energy. Energy input (absorption) is required to move the electron away from the nucleus. The absorption spectrum would show a continuous spectrum with black lines (where the light is absorbed) at the wavelength corresponding to this particular transition.\n  - Visible light $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    Transitions from higher energy levels to $n = 2$ represent the Balmer Series in the hydrogen atom and emit light in the visible spectrum. A transition in the opposite direction from $n = 2$ to a higher energy level will involve the same magnitude of energy, just absorbed rather than emitted.\n  - Shorter wavelength $\\checkmark$\n    $n = 4$ to $n = 1$ is a higher energy transition due to the greater distance to $n = 1$ resulting from the convergence of the energy levels. Higher energy corresponds to a shorter wavelength. $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    On the diagram in part (i), the distance from  $n = 4$ to $n = 1$ is greater than the distance from $n = 2$ to $n = 5$, and therefore more energy is involved in the $4 \\longrightarrow 1$ transition.\n    Using the equations $E = hf$ and $c = \\lambda f$, one can see that energy and frequency are directly related, but frequency and wavelength are inversely related. Therefore, energy and wavelength are inversely related. The energy increases, so the wavelength decreases.\n\n- \n  - $(1228\\,\\text{kJ mol}^{-1})(\\dfrac{1000\\,\\text{J}}{1\\,\\text{kJ}})(\\dfrac{1\\,\\text{mol}}{6.02\\times 10^{23}}) = \\answer{2.040\\times 10^{-18}\\,\\text{J}}\\,\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    The energy value provided states the energy for a mole of electrons  (kJ mol$^{-1}$) undergoing this energy transition. The calculation involves converting $kJ$ to $J$ and dividing  by Avagadro's constant to determine the energy value for a single electron.\n  - $\\lambda = \\dfrac{hc}{E} = \\dfrac{(6.63\\times 10^{-34}\\,\\text{J s})(3.00\\times 10^8\\,\\text{m s}^{-1})}{(2.040\\times 10^{-18}\\,\\text{J})} = \\answer{9.750\\times 10^{-8}\\,\\text{m}}\\,\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    The calculation involves the equations, $E = hf$ and $c = \\lambda f$\n  - Ultraviolet $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    Using the electromagnetic spectrum (table 3 in the data booklet), a wavelength with the magnitude $10^{-8}$ to $10^{-9}$ would fall in the UV portion of the spectrum.\n  - Transitions between energy levels within the atom involve specific amounts of energy. The transition from $4 \\longrightarrow 1$ in the hydrogen atom will always emit the same amount of energy and produce the same spectral line. $\\checkmark$\n    The photons emitted by the transition $4 \\longrightarrow 1$ are of a specific frequency and have discrete values because the electrons in the energy levels hold specific amounts of energy. $\\checkmark$\n    The response should describe the Bohr concept that the electrons reside in specific energy levels and therefore have specific amounts of energy. As they transition to lower energy levels as in 4 $\\longrightarrow$ 1, photons are emitted with discrete amounts of energy having specific wavelengths and frequencies, they are said to be quantized.\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\n    The Bohr model puts electrons in specific energy levels, Their energy in any particular level can be calculated. In the hydrogen atom, transitions from higher to lower energy levels emit photons of light of specific wavelength and frequency, they therefore carry an exact or discrete amount of energy and are quantized.\n\n",
