      'Ionization energy data for the elements can be used to provide evidence for energy levels and sublevels within the atom.\n\n- The diagram below shows the amount of energy required to remove the first 10 electrons from a period 3 element.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/936356f8-e31b-4bf2-99a4-07f670f2d94b/images/e1a82b9f-5b5a-4cb0-a4b3-1a3d8405c221/CH0786a.png)\n\n\n  \n  - Write an equation that represents the third ionization energy of an element. You can use A as the symbol for the unknown element. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  - Identify the period 3 element and explain how the ionization data shown above supports your response. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n  - Explain why the ionization data increases as subsequent electrons are removed from the atom. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  - Write the electron configuration for the commonly formed ion of this period 3 element. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n\n- The diagram below shows the first ionization energies of the elements across period 3.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/936356f8-e31b-4bf2-99a4-07f670f2d94b/images/6eee7b19-a1b4-45d8-880e-a5473303b658/CH0786b.png)\n\n\n  \n  - Explain how the first ionization data shown can be used to support the existence of the $s$ and $p$ sublevels of period 3. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n  - Explain why argon has such a high first ionization energy. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- \n  - $\\ce{A^2+(g) -> A^3+(g) + e-}\\,\\checkmark\\checkmark$\nAward M2 for state symbols.\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nIonization energy is the energy required to remove an electron from a ground$-$state gas$-$phase atom or ion. The removal of the third successive electron would come from the ion of the element that has already lost 2 electrons ($\\ce{A^{2+}}$). Removal of the third electron would change the ion to $\\ce{A^{3+}}$.\n  - Magnesium  / Mg $\\checkmark$\nlarge jump between 2$^{nd}$ and 3$^{rd}$ ionization energy, 3$^{rd}$electron from inner energy level $\\checkmark$\ntwo valence electrons $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nLooking at the graph, there is a larger step (nonlinear) increase in the subsequent ionization energies for the removal of the third electron. This means the first two electrons are removed from the valence energy level, while the third is removed from an inner energy level, in this case the second energy level since the element is in period 3.\n  - more positively changed ion, stronger attraction to the nucleus $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nSince ionization energy is the energy required to completely move the electron from the atom or ion, as the charge on the nucleus increases, the ionization energy must therefore increase.\n  - $\\ce{1s^2\\,2s^2\\,2p^6}$ $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nThe period 3 element is magnesium with two valence electrons in the $3s$ sublevel. Losing these two electrons leaves a the period 2 energy level, with $s$ and $p$ sublevels complete.\n\n- \n  - drop in ionization energy from Mg to Al $\\checkmark$\nelectrons in $3p$ subshell partially shielded by $3s$ electrons  $\\checkmark$\ndrop in the ionization energy moving from P to S $\\checkmark$\nfourth electron in $3p$ subshell experiences increased $\\ce{e-}-\\ce{e-}$ repulsion $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nThe trend of ionization energy across period 3 is generally upward due to the increasing nuclear charge pulling the outer electrons closer. However, the data also show irregularities that can only be explained by sublevels. The first occurs between magnesium and aluminium: in aluminium, the electron removed is from a $3p$ orbital, which lies at slightly higher energy and is shielded by the inner 3s orbital. This makes it easier to remove than the $3s$ electron in magnesium. A second dip occurs between phosphorus and sulfur. Phosphorus has three unpaired $3p$ electrons, but sulfur has a fourth $3p$ electron that must pair with one of the others. The repulsion between two electrons in the same orbital lowers the energy required to remove one, creating the observed decrease. These two dips are direct experimental evidence that period 3 contains both $3s$ and $3p$ sublevels.\n  - Ar has highest effective nuclear charge , same shielding $\\checkmark$\n    $\\underline{\\textrm{Further Explanation}}$:\nArgon lies at the end of period 3, where the nuclear charge is greatest. Its outer electrons are still in the $n=3$ shell, but they experience a strong effective nuclear charge because shielding from inner electrons is relatively constant across the period. This strong attraction between nucleus and outer $3p$ electrons requires much more energy to remove them, so argon shows the highest first ionization energy of period 3.\n\n',
